(71, 4, '2011-05-17 01:32:37', '2011-05-17 07:32:37', 'Kids, today we are going to talk about <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure_Shell">SSH</a> authentication, the public-key based type to be specific. This is an  important topic for several reasons, but mainly because it allows to use  SSH without needing to enter a password. This becomes really convenient  if:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>You are a sysadmin and need to streamline your daily tasks that involve SSHing to remote machines.</li>\r\n	<li>You have automated tasks that need to execute remote commands.</li>\r\n	<li>You use <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Git_%28software%29">git</a> and have a remote central server where every pushes to and new builds/releases are cut from.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOne thing Id like to be clear on, is that I will <strong>not</strong> be guiding you through the setup of public-key based authentication (PKBA), there are countless articles about that on the <a href="http://www.google.com/search?hl=en&amp;q=ssh+public+key+authentication&amp;aq=f&amp;aqi=g1g-c3g6&amp;aql=&amp;oq=">Interwebz</a> and it would be redundant. What Id like to explain here are the basic concepts.\r\n\r\nWhen you do\r\n<pre>\r\nssh-keygen -t rsa\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\nYou will end up with two files id_rsa and id_rsa.pub, the first one is your private key and the latter is your public key.\r\n\r\nImagine that you have access to a fort, but every time you want to get in you have to shout your password through the door. Now if you do this a couple of times a month it is no big deal, but if you do it several times each hour, you might get a sore throat! Now if you could install a deadbolt in that door, a deadbolt you have the key for, then you can come and go as you please, and save yourself from being aphonic for days.\r\n\r\nWhen you take your id_rsa.pub file and add its contents to the authorized_keys file on the remote machine(s), it is like you are installing your own deadbolt on the fort machine. So your id_rsa and id_rsa.pub files literally equate to a key and a deadbolt, surprise.\r\n\r\nNow the really cool part about PKBA is that unlike physical deadbolts and keys, the whole process is automatic you dont have to lift a finger.\r\n\r\nOne thing you should know is that if you want this scheme to work, youll have to have your private key on your local machine (where you start ssh from) and your public key should be in the authorized_keys file on the remote machine.', 'SSH 101: Public-Key Based Authentication', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'ssh-101-public-key-based-authentication', '', '', '2011-05-17 01:33:03', '2011-05-17 07:33:03', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8080/geeksomnio/?p=71', 0, 'post', '', 0),
